        "title": "Will Cloud Dataflow throw exceptions when performing autoscaling?",
        "body": "<p>We are currently using Dataflow to run a streaming job. In that job, we perform datastore transactions of the following form:<\/p>\n\n<pre class=\"lang-java prettyprint-override\"><code>Entity task;\nTransaction txn = datastore.newTransaction();\ntry {\n  task = txn.get(taskKey);\n  update(task);\n  txn.put(task);\n  txn.commit();\n} finally {\n  if (txn.isActive()) {\n    txn.rollback();\n  }\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>In the event of scaling up/down, we see a lot of exceptions that activate the <code>rollback<\/code>. This would mean that the transaction is still active and that the <code>commit<\/code> statement was never executed. We do not, however see datastore exceptions in this case.<\/p>\n\n<p>We suspect that Dataflow cancels the active processing of elements and retries them in the scaled pipeline. This would then throw an unhandled exception and execute the <code>finally<\/code> steps. For some elements this would be <em>before<\/em> the <code>commit<\/code>, which would explain the behaviour. <\/p>\n\n<p>Also, the exception is maybe not exposed by Dataflow as these are internal ones.<\/p>\n\n<p>If the above is not the case, it would seem that the transaction implementation is faulty, which we -of course- assume is correct.<\/p>\n\n<p>Is the reasoning correct? Or is there an other explanation?<\/p>\n",
